"'''A Hunter's Fate: Greedo's Tale'''" is a short story written by [[Tom Veitch|Tom]] and [[Martha Veitch]] for the short-story anthology ''[[Tales from the Mos Eisley Cantina]]'', published by [[Bantam Spectra]] in [[1995]], concerning the backstory of the [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]] [[Greedo/Legends|Greedo]]. It was adapted into a [[A Hunter's Fate: Greedo's Tale (webstrip)|webstrip]] by [[Pablo Hidalgo]] for [[Hyperspace: The Official Star Wars Fan Club|Hyperspace]].

==Plot summary==
===[[4 BBY/Legends|4 BBY]]===
A teenage [[Greedo/Legends|Greedo]] and his younger brother, [[Pqweeduk]], explore the various [[Cave/Legends|caves]] inside the [[Jungle/Legends|jungles]] of their adopted home world. They discover the remains of three old [[Rodian/Legends|Rodian]] [[Starship/Legends|starships]] inside one of the caves. Greedo returns to his hut and asks his [[Parent/Legends|mother]], [[Neela]], about the ships. Neela explains that many Rodians made a pilgrimage to this [[Planet/Legends|planet]] to escape the [[Rodian Clan Wars|clan wars]] that had taken [[Greedo the Elder|Greedo's father]] away from them.

Shortly after this event, a Rodian [[Warlord/Legends|warlord]] of the [[Chattza clan/Legends|Chattza Clan]] named [[Navik/Legends|Navik the Red]] finds the jungle colony and begins [[Death/Legends|slaughtering]] as many of the pacifist Rodians as he can. Neela takes her [[Youngling/Legends|children]] and along with her brothers, [[Nok (Rodian)|Nok]] and [[Teeku]], they board one of the starships and escape. Nok [[Pilot/Legends|pilots]] them to a heavily populated area in the hopes that they can start a new life for themselves. He takes them to the [[Smuggler/Legends|smugglers]]' moon&mdash;[[Nar Shaddaa/Legends|Nar Shaddaa]].

===[[0 BBY/Legends|Four years later]]===
[[Greedo/Legends|Greedo]] has been living the past four [[Standard year/Legends|years]] on [[Level 88]] in the [[Corellian Sector (Nar Shaddaa)/Legends|Corellian Sector]] of [[Nar Shaddaa/Legends|Nar Shaddaa]]. In that time, he has befriended a [[Skup/Legends|Sionian Skup]] named [[Anky Fremp]] and has eked out a living as a petty [[Thief/Legends|thief]]. One day, Greedo notices the [[Droid/Legends|droid]] [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]] known as [[Gorm (cyborg)|Gorm the Dissolver]] preparing to [[Death/Legends|kill]] two other hunters named [[Spurch Goa]] and [[Dyyz Nataz]]. Greedo, hoping to establish some connections within the bounty-hunting community, shoots Gorm in the back, disabling him. Spurch is grateful for the assistance and decides to take Greedo under his wing. What Greedo doesn't know, however, is that Spurch despises [[Rodian/Legends|Rodians]], and merely lets the young thief tag along so long as he is of use to him.

Greedo decides that he now wants to become the most famous bounty hunter in [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]]. He learns that the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] maintains a secret munitions warehouse on Level 88. He sells the information to Spurch, who in turn sells it to the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Empire]]. With the [[Currency/Legends|money]] he receives, Greedo prepares to acquire his own [[Starship/Legends|starship]]. He goes to [[Shug Ninx]]'s repair shop where he finds an [[Corsair/Legends|Incom corsair]] that would be perfect for him. He even has a name for it&mdash;the ''[[Manka Hunter]]''. The ship needs a couple of [[Power coupling/Legends|power couplings]], however, so he tries to steal some from a [[YT-1300 light freighter/Legends|YT-1300 light freighter]] stored at the garage. The freighter's owners, [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] and [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]], catch him in the act and interrogate him. Han decides to let Greedo keep the couplings in exchange for his [[Rancor/Legends|rancor]]-skin coat.

Before long, [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] uses the information he has received and sends two [[Gamma-class assault shuttle/Legends|''Gamma''-class assault shuttles]] to Nar Shaddaa to destroy the Rebel storage facilities. Greedo becomes concerned as he learns that his family's housing development is very near the siege. Shortly thereafter, Greedo decides to leave Nar Shaddaa and begin his bounty-hunting career in earnest. He travels to the [[Outer Rim Territories/Legends|Outer Rim Territories]] world [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]], along with Spurch and Dyyz. Spurch manages to gain Greedo an audience with the notorious [[Gangster/Legends|gangster]], [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba Desilijic Tiure]]. Jabba decides to put the young Rodian's enthusiasm to the test and offers him exclusive bounty rights to capture Han Solo.

Greedo encounters Han twice in the port city of [[Mos Eisley/Legends|Mos Eisley]] and tries to force him to pay off a debt owed to Jabba. Han tells Greedo to return the next [[Standard day/Legends|day]] and he'll have Jabba's money ready for him. Greedo acquiesces and meets Han the following afternoon at [[Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina/Legends|Chalmun's Spaceport Cantina]]. The two get into a small argument which ends with Han pulling his [[Blaster/Legends|blaster]] out and shooting Greedo in the chest, killing him. From the sidelines, Spurch Goa snickers at the fact that he was able to manipulate Greedo into gunning for Han, safe in the knowledge that the [[Corellian/Legends|Corellian]] would outshoot him. Spurch had accepted a retainer by two Rodians named [[Thuku]] and [[Neesh/Legends|Neesh]] to have Greedo killed.

==Continuity==
The story made a number of assumptions regarding [[Greedo/Legends|Greedo's]] history that have since been disproven in the canon established by [[George Lucas]]. In the story, the [[Rodian/Legends|Rodian]] was nineteen [[Standard year/Legends|years]] old at the time of his [[Death/Legends|death]]. A deleted scene from ''[[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace]]'' ([[1999]]) showed Greedo as a [[Youngling/Legends|child]] around the same age as [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], and a denizen of [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]] at the time, which would make him much older than nineteen at his death.

''[[The New Essential Guide to Characters]]'' ([[2002]]) attempted to preserve both stories by presenting the Episode I Greedo as “[[Greedo the Elder]]”, [[Parent/Legends|father]] to the younger Greedo depicted in ''A Hunter's Fate''. However, [[Sphere of Influence]], a [[The Clone Wars: Season Three|season three episode]] of ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' ([[2010]]), made this fix impossible, as it was clear that Lucas intended Greedo to be an older, luckless [[Bounty hunter/Legends|hunter]] who has spent years on Tatooine trying to make a name for himself.<ref name="TERC" />

